    <h3>Is Claude Code better than Cursor for coding?</h3>
    <p>It depends on your workflow. Claude Code excels at large codebase analysis and refactoring thanks to its massive 200K-token context window. Cursor offers a more integrated IDE experience with real-time codebase indexing and natural language editing. For pure code quality on complex tasks, Claude Code has an edge. For day-to-day development speed, Cursor is often faster.</p>
    <h3>How much does Claude Code cost compared to Cursor?</h3>
    <p>Claude Code Pro costs $20 per month (or $100 per month for Claude Max with unlimited usage). Cursor Pro costs $20 per month with 500 fast requests and unlimited slow requests. Both offer free tiers with limited usage.</p>
    <h3>Which has a larger context window?</h3>
    <p>Claude Code supports up to 200K tokens (approximately 150,000 words) in its context window, which is significantly larger than Cursor's effective context window. This makes Claude Code superior for analyzing entire codebases or large files in a single session.</p>
    <h3>Can I use Claude Code inside my existing IDE?</h3>
    <p>Claude Code runs as a terminal-based CLI tool that works alongside any editor including VS Code, JetBrains IDEs, Vim, and Neovim. Cursor is a standalone fork of VS Code, so you must switch to it as your primary editor to use its full feature set.</p>
    <h3>Is Claude Code or Cursor better for beginners?</h3>
    <p>Cursor is generally more beginner-friendly because it provides a visual IDE interface with inline suggestions, natural language editing through Composer, and an intuitive chat panel. Claude Code requires comfort with terminal commands and may have a steeper learning curve for developers new to CLI tools.</p>
